result.execSummary:
The defendant Ryan Allan Swan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ryan Allan Swan in court with attorney Andrew I. Martinez.  Rick C Spoentgen and intern Emma B. appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court states case and State states appearances and status.  Asst. AG Colin Roth also appears.  Second motion to reconsider filed by State in re: to order from the Court.  Court has reviewed all records and makes her ruling.  Court would grant request by State to have their own tests performed.  State points out the Court's ruling precludes him from being able to request further testing now - cites two sentences he feels preclude his testing re: 971.23.  Ruling as it stands would not allow the State to have the evidence back for further testing.  Atty Martinez responds.  State responds.  Atty Martinez has nothing to add.  Court reaffirms it's denial of the motion to vacate.  State requests that the order contain specific language as to "when the results are issued..." and then how long before the results would be turned over.  Atty Martinez responds/has no objection.  Court will prepare an order and will have to cross some of these bridges when they get to them.  State questions possible conflict w/crime lab.  Atty Roth notes tests have been completed and they can be provided in a timely manner and states the lab has a procedure internally re: re-testing.  Crime lab stands ready to follow whatever order the Court issues.  Atty Martinez states he hasn't seen the results yet but assumes they'll be provided fairly quickly.  Requests 45 days to make a decision.  State doesn't object to 45 days and requests status be set now.  Atty Martinez agrees.  Court sets status hearing.  State requests formal order be provided as to the Court's ruling today.  Atty Martinez agrees to draft such order.  Bond continued.  Status conference scheduled for September 1, 2017 at 08:30 am.

Attorney Adam Raabe in court.  Rick C Spoentgen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  State states appearance.  Atty. Raabe states appearance.  Motion to dismiss complaint.  Court review motion and brief/opposition by State.  Exculpatory evidence was not preserved is what defense is stating.  Did evidence exist or not.  The middle is missing.  Evidence was potentially exculpatory and bad faith.  Atty. Spoentgen makes statement.  Atty. Raabe makes argument - evidence to preserve.  The video after incident if destroyed in bad faith.  Atty. Spoentgen doesn't agree and makes argument.  Negligent on BPD detective Drexler is not the same as exculpatory.  No showing made of bad faith on BPD.  Atty. Raabe makes argument and BPD making remarks to stop asking for discovery and may need to have evidentiary hearing but believes made enough argument on video/policy violation.  Atty. Spoentgen makes statement/argument.  Court states was there bad faith shown - based on the statements - there wasn't.  Court is going to allow an evidentiary hearing.  Burden of defense that there was in fact bad faith.  Court takes up defense motion for discovery.  Discovery of 11 photos of victim.  State makes argument, not relevant.  Atty. Raabe states not a brady violation, is a discovery violation.  Atty. Spoentgen makes argument.  Court will take under advisement and rule at evidentiary hearing.  
Evidentiary hearing scheduled for October 24, 2016 at 10:00 am.
